The paper discusses connections between circuit complexity and proof complexity, which are both central topics in theoretical computer science. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces certain propositional axioms satisfied by any Boolean circuit computing PIT, which relates to information theory and coding theory, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also sheds light on the relationships between previous algebraic proof systems, which relates to algebraic geometry and algebraic topology, making cs.CG (Computational Geometry) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses lower bounds on the number of lines in Polynomial Calculus proofs, which relates to discrete mathematics and combinatorics, making cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) possible sub-categories as well.
